### Step 4 — Run no-transmit sensitivity tests

Goal: determine message counts without waiting for UART transmit.

Run capture/compress only:

```bash
cd /home/pi/BM_Devel_Pi

LOG="cron_logs/sensitivity_notx_$(date -u +%Y%m%dT%H%M%SZ).log"

timeout 900s /usr/bin/python3 -u main_pi_camera.py \
  --skip-time-window \
  2>&1 | tee "$LOG"

echo "===== SIZE CHECK ====="
grep -E "Runtime image_pipeline|converted_size|HEIC helper completed|Compressed image saved|Saved [0-9]+ buffer|Image pipeline geometry|Libcamera metadata loaded" "$LOG" | tail -100
```

Then adjust YAML and repeat.

Candidate test matrix:

```text
2030×1142 Q20
2030×1142 Q10
1920×1080 Q20
1920×1080 Q10
1600×900 Q20
1600×900 Q10
```

Acceptance target:

```text
<150 buffers preferred
<180 buffers acceptable
>200 buffers risky for 20-minute power window
```

### Step 5 — Run local HEIC compression on coral scientists’ reference JPEGs

The user has high-res underwater JPEGs from coral scientists. New agent should build or reuse a local script to:

1. Load high-res JPEG.
2. Apply same center/crop aspect ratio if needed.
3. Downsample to candidate output sizes.
4. HEIC encode at Q10/Q20/Q30.
5. Estimate base64 chars and 300-byte message count.
6. Create a comparison table.

Message count estimate:

```python
import base64, math
heic_bytes = Path("image.heic").read_bytes()
base64_chars = len(base64.b64encode(heic_bytes))
buffers = math.ceil(base64_chars / 300)
minimum_uart_seconds = buffers * 5
```

Output table should include:

```text
source_file
output_width
output_height
heic_quality
heic_bytes
base64_chars
buffer_count_300
min_uart_sec_at_5s
min_uart_min_at_5s
```

Also create a contact sheet with visual comparisons.

